stated previously, you will be prompted in Visual Studio if Developer mode is not enabled.","pos":[5311,5404]},{"content":"On the mobile device family:","pos":[5410,5438]},{"content":"Enable developer mode to deploy apps from Visual Studio and debug them on the device.","pos":[5444,5529]},{"content":"You can tap the file to install any .appx sent to you via email or on an SD card.","pos":[5535,5616]},{"content":"Do not install apps from unverified sources.","pos":[5617,5661]},{"content":"Tip","pos":[5665,5668]},{"content":"There are several tools you can use to deploy an app from a Windows 10 PC to a Windows 10 mobile device.","pos":[5673,5777]},{"content":"Both devices must be connected to the same subnet of the network by a wired or wireless connection, or they must be connected by USB.","pos":[5778,5911]},{"content":"Either of the ways listed installs only the app package (.appx); they do not install certificates.","pos":[5912,6010]},{"content":"Use the Windows 10 Application Deployment (WinAppDeployCmd) tool.","pos":[6016,6081]},{"content":"Learn more about <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>the WinAppDeployCmd tool<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt203806.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[6082,6188],"source":" Learn more about [the WinAppDeployCmd tool](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt203806.aspx)."},{"content":"Starting in Windows 10, Version 1511, you can use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Device Portal<ept id=\"p1\">](#device_portal)</ept> to deploy from your browser to a mobile device running Windows 10, Version 1511 or later.","pos":[6193,6364],"source":"Starting in Windows 10, Version 1511, you can use [Device Portal](#device_portal) to deploy from your browser to a mobile device running Windows 10, Version 1511 or later."},{"content":"Use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Apps<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> page in Device Portal (<ph id=\"ph1\">&amp;lt;</ph>IP<ph id=\"ph2\">&amp;gt;</ph>/appmanager.md) to upload an app package (.appx) and install it on the